hands_on_practices.solution:
We model the system as the product of three paraxial ray-transfer matrices acting on the ray vector $\begin{pmatrix} y \\ \alpha \end{pmatrix}$:
1) Refraction at the first (spherical) surface from index $n_{1}=1$ to $n_{2}=n$ with radius $R$.
2) Translation by the central thickness $d$ inside the lens.
3) Refraction at the second (plane) surface from index $n_{1}=n$ to $n_{2}=1$.

In the $(y,\alpha)$ convention, the refraction at a spherical surface obeys $n_{2}\alpha_{2}=n_{1}\alpha_{1}-y\,\frac{n_{2}-n_{1}}{R}$, giving the matrix
$$
S_{1}=\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 0 \\
\frac{n_{1}-n_{2}}{n_{2}R} & \frac{n_{1}}{n_{2}}
\end{pmatrix}
=\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 0 \\
\frac{1-n}{nR} & \frac{1}{n}
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
Propagation over a distance $d$ in a homogeneous medium leaves the angle unchanged and adds $d\alpha$ to the height, so
$$
T(d)=\begin{pmatrix}
1 & d \\
0 & 1
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
Refraction at a plane surface (radius $R\to\infty$) enforces $n_{2}\alpha_{2}=n_{1}\alpha_{1}$, hence
$$
S_{2}=\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 0 \\
0 & \frac{n_{1}}{n_{2}}
\end{pmatrix}
=\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 0 \\
0 & n
\end{pmatrix}
\quad\text{for }n_{1}=n,\; n_{2}=1.
$$
The total system matrix from just before the first surface to just after the second surface is
$$
M=S_{2}\,T(d)\,S_{1}.
$$
Compute $T(d)\,S_{1}$ first:
$$
T(d)\,S_{1}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
1 & d \\
0 & 1
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 0 \\
\frac{1-n}{nR} & \frac{1}{n}
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
1+\frac{d(1-n)}{nR} & \frac{d}{n} \\
\frac{1-n}{nR} & \frac{1}{n}
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
Then multiply by $S_{2}$ on the left:
$$
M=S_{2}\,(T(d)\,S_{1})=
\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 0 \\
0 & n
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
1+\frac{d(1-n)}{nR} & \frac{d}{n} \\
\frac{1-n}{nR} & \frac{1}{n}
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
1+\frac{d(1-n)}{nR} & \frac{d}{n} \\
n\frac{1-n}{nR} & n\frac{1}{n}
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
Therefore, the element $A=M_{11}$ is
$$
A=1+\frac{d(1-n)}{nR}=1-\frac{(n-1)d}{nR}.
$$
